## The Last Mile of Security Work

Day 84 built the visualization framework — the ISSO operational dashboard, the Health IT Manager monthly summary, and the AO one-page quarterly visual. Each dashboard was designed around a core principle: information at the right level of aggregation, honest representation of Yellow and Red indicators, and interpretation rather than just data display. The dashboards are the structured reporting layer. Day 85 is about something different — the unstructured, high-stakes communication moments where the ISSO needs to convey a risk or request in a way that produces a decision.

Scheduled reporting delivers information on a known cadence to a prepared audience. The communication challenges I want to examine today are the harder ones: the mid-quarter AO conversation about the CP-2 AT RISK condition, the request to the Executive Director for resources to implement the phishing simulation program, the moment when an incident is unfolding and the ISSO has to brief a clinical leader who has never heard the word "GuardDuty" and needs to know whether to invoke clinical downtime procedures in the next five minutes.

These communication moments cannot be handled with a template. They require the ability to convey the right information, in the right frame, at the right level of detail, under conditions that may not be comfortable.

---

## What I Worked On Today

Risk communication is addressed in NIST SP 800-30 Rev 1 (risk communication as an organizational risk management function) and in the broader communications literature on audience-centered communication. The core challenge is not translating technical content into simpler language — it is identifying what the specific audience needs to make their specific decision and providing exactly that, organized to support the decision rather than to demonstrate the communicator's expertise.

Today I work through four specific communication scenarios from the OpenMRS program — each with a different audience, different stakes, and different communication requirements — and examine what makes each communication effective or ineffective.

---

## What Actually Clicked for Me

The insight that clarified risk communication today is the distinction between information transfer and decision support.

Information transfer is the default mode of technical communication: I know something, you need to know it, I will tell you. The mental model is a transaction — ISSO sends data, audience receives data, communication complete.

Decision support is a different mode: I understand what decision you need to make, I understand what information you need to make it well, and I will provide exactly that information organized to support your decision. The mental model is a service — the ISSO's communication serves the audience's decision-making need, not the ISSO's need to convey expertise or cover compliance obligations.

The difference is visible in the executive elevator pitch structure. An information-transfer version of the MFA pitch says: "OpenMRS lacks MFA enforcement, creating vulnerability to phishing and brute force attacks. We should implement AWS Cognito TOTP integration." This is accurate and technically complete. It does not support the Executive Director's decision.

The Executive Director's decision is not "should we implement TOTP?" — it is "should I allocate budget and organizational attention to this security initiative rather than competing priorities?" Supporting that decision requires: what is the risk if we do nothing (patient data breach, HIPAA enforcement, reputational damage), what is the cost of the initiative (implementation time, staff training disruption, ongoing operational overhead), and what is the organizational outcome if we proceed (reduced breach likelihood, HIPAA compliance assurance, operational continuity). The ISSO's job is to provide that information, organized around the decision, not to provide a technical briefing that the executive then has to translate into a budget decision.

