## A Real-World Example That Made This Click

The 2am incident briefing scenario — communication under pressure where the wrong approach wastes the first minute of a time-critical conversation on technical context — is directly illustrated by the **2017 Equifax breach communication failures**.

When Equifax's security team identified the breach, the internal communication to leadership was initially technical in framing — focused on what had been found and the investigation underway, rather than on the decisions that leadership needed to make about customer notification, regulatory disclosure, and remediation authorization. The gap between the breach discovery and the public notification (six weeks) reflects in part the communication failures that delayed organizational decision-making.

The Equifax case is not simply a technical failure — it is a communication failure. The people with authority to make decisions about notification and remediation did not receive communication organized to support those decisions. By the time leadership was fully engaged, the window for effective crisis response had narrowed significantly.

For the OpenMRS program, the 2am scenario design — 30 seconds of situation summary, clear decision framing, ISSO recommendation, respects Health IT Manager authority — is the communication discipline that ensures decision-makers are engaged at the moment their decisions matter, not after the technical team has spent an hour investigating.

