## What I Am Still Thinking About

The annual authorization recommendation is the most consequential communication the ISSO produces, and it is also the communication that is most tempting to hedge. Writing "the security program is functioning and I recommend continued authorization" creates a record of the ISSO's judgment. If something goes wrong in the second year that the ISSO's recommendation did not anticipate, that recommendation is part of the documentation trail.

This is the genuine accountability of the ISSO role, and I do not think hedging is the right response to it. An ISSO whose recommendations are consistently hedged — "monitoring suggests no material concerns, but ongoing vigilance is recommended" — is not providing the governance function that the AO needs. The AO pays a professional for a professional judgment. The hedge is a way of appearing to provide a recommendation while avoiding the accountability that comes with one.

The right response to the accountability concern is to be specific rather than to hedge. A recommendation that says "continue authorization, with particular attention to the RTO margin trend and the phishing simulation program gap" is a specific professional judgment that can be evaluated. It creates accountability for the ISSO — and it provides the AO with a genuine basis for their own decision, rather than a document that reads as comprehensive while containing no actual recommendation.

Specificity is the antidote to the hedge. The more specific the recommendation — naming the concerns, naming the conditions, naming what would change the recommendation — the more valuable and accountable the communication.

